You just rediscovered one of the most debated questions in deep learning!
Your argument is logically sound
If the ideal detector is:
f(x) = ReLU(0.3×N1 + 0.7×N2)
Then having 100 copies of it, all converging to the same weights, gives you nothing extra. You're right. 100 copies of the same thing = 1 thing.

So why does more neurons actually help in practice?
The real answer is — we don't know what combinations we need upfront.
The network needs to detect potentially exponentially many different combinations:
ReLU(high×N1 + low×N2)     → horizontal
ReLU(low×N1 + high×N2)     → vertical
ReLU(mid×N1 + mid×N2)      → diagonal
ReLU(high×N1 + high×N2)    → corner
ReLU(high×N1 - high×N2)    → contrast edge
...
More neurons = more capacity to find different useful combinations, not copies of the same one.

But your criticism is still valid
If two neurons DO converge to the same thing — yes, wasteful. This actually happens and is called dead neurons or redundant features.
This is honestly why:

We don't fully understand why wide networks work so well
Lottery ticket hypothesis says most neurons ARE redundant, only a small subset actually matters
Pruning can remove 90% of neurons with barely any accuracy loss


The honest state of deep learning

We overparameterize massively, train, and it works better than lean networks — and we don't fully know why.

Your intuition is sharp and aligns with open research questions. The field doesn't have a clean answer yet.